    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-03-20T16:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-03-20T16:00:00-05:00" n="981"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d981">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.0011 LCC/21: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Harriman</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-03-21T00:00:00+03:00"
                            >March 21, 1944—midnight</date>.<lb/>[Received March 22—11
                        a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>961. Department’s 312, February 16, 4 p.m.<note n="14" xml:id="d981fn14">See
                        footnote 13, above.</note> In conversation with Vyshinski<note n="15"
                        xml:id="d981fn15">Andrey Yanuaryevich Vyshinsky, First Deputy People’s
                        Commissar for Foreign Affairs of the Soviet Union.</note> on March 21st I
                    referred to the participation of the Soviet Government on the London Propaganda
                    Committee concerning which I had written to Molotov<note n="16"
                        xml:id="d981fn16">Vyacheslav Mikhailovich Molotov, People’s Commissar for
                        Foreign Affairs of the Soviet Union.</note> on February 26 and inquired
                    whether the Foreign Office had made any decision in the premises. Vyshinski
                    stated that the subject was complicated in substance and in its technical
                    aspects. However, he indicated that a reply to my note would be sent to the
                    Embassy in the near future.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Harriman</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
